snippet.textDisplay: No doubt Adrián's brilliant footwork and quite bad finishing from Everton saved Liverpool through the first half hour, as the Toffees obviously attacked the side where inexperienced Yasser Larouci had to step in. But Theo Walcott was on the edge as Everton's best player, and I don't think Milner would have done much better, as preventing these attacks also was the fellow midfielders and central denfenders responsability. Still, Larouci also improved throughout the game and was brilliant in second half, and the blue and whites seemed to lose their motivation. Should not happen against so many junior players. When Larouci came on the average age of the Liverpool's team skydived down to 22. Ancelotti's left eyebrow went up to 1 o'clock and he has some work to do with his players' fundamental psyche.

snippet.textDisplay: I wonder if Everton fans are still on cloud 9 over the fact Ancelotti is their manager. Everyone was saying Arsenal should have gone for Ancelotti over Arteta because of experience and what he has won. The Arsenal board were smart enough to learn from their mistake which is "Experience does not always mean one is destined to Excell". They hired Emery and it didn't work out and now they are like okay UK what lets go for something different. Arsenal have Arteta who after a masterclass against Chelsea and Man United Midway through the season (when Arsenal are in relegation form) changes everything about how the team plays and is looking to be a serious potential boss of a manager. I'm yet to see any difference with Everton under Ancelotti and the fact that they play a full strength squad against Liverpool kids and still get beaten convincingly is even more appalling.
